Sara Greenstein


   
Whether she's just arrived back from a week of meetings in China or getting ready to jet to Germany or California, Sara Greenstein always finds time for the Bagel.The unpretentious breakfast diner and deli on Broadway in Lakeview has been a Sunday morning ritual for Ms. Greenstein since before she and her husband, Jay, were married 3½ years ago.
These days, they come to the Bagel earlier than they used to in a concession to their 2-year-old son, Matthew, who's yet to appreciate sleeping late on weekends. Ms. Greenstein held Matthew's birthday party at the restaurant and often invites friends to join her there.
"It's accommodated all stages of our lives," she says in between sips of Diet Coke and bites of over-easy eggs. "Now, if I'm flying out on a Sunday, we come on Saturday. I make the best of every moment I have."
STEPHEN J. SERIO
In the past five years, she's managed to shoehorn in personal milestones like getting married and having a child between the non-stop pace of her responsibilities at Northbrook-based product safety testing firm Underwriters Laboratories Inc.
She presides over the sales and business development activities for UL, the nation's preeminent safety certification and testing firm for everything from electric frying pans to fire alarms. She's been a key architect of an overhaul of the century-old non-profit company to make it more entrepreneurial and less bureaucratic.
She's also been the catalyst for UL's expansion overseas in recent years, making the case that the public pressure for more safety standards and product testing in developing countries like China and India presents a big opportunity for UL to increase revenue and its global footprint.
 9 TO 10 A.M.The best time for breakfast at the Bagel.
Colleagues say her opinions carry weight with other senior leaders because she gets results.
"She's able to select a team and lead them and drive solutions," says Sajeev Jesudas, president of UL's international operations. "A lot of leaders fall apart on implementation."
Ms. Greenstein, who was raised on a farm in Central Illinois and now lives in Chicago's Old Town neighborhood, maintains a travel schedule that regularly takes her to the headquarters of some of the world's best-known companies to shore up customer relationships.
When she's not on the road, evenings at home are often spent conversing via e-mail with managers in Japan or China, where it's early in the morning. And she gets to the office by 6 a.m. to catch managers in Europe before they leave for the day.
"She's been very involved in the customer relationships," says Al Scolnik, vice-president for testing services at the Virginia-based National Electrical Manufacturers Assn. "All the trouble issues stop at her desk."
There's been no shortage of those since Ms. Greenstein, a former consultant with Andersen Consulting, arrived at UL in 2002. After decades of having a near monopoly on testing work in the United States, by the late 1990s UL found itself facing several competitors that had sliced its marketshare to about 50%. Manufacturers had started taking products to lesser-known testing labs to avoid UL's notoriously slow and costly testing process.
The company's revenue growth nearly came to a standstill by 2001. For the first time in its history, UL laid off employees, eliminating about 10% of its U.S. workforce by 2004.
Ms. Greenstein was put in charge of realigning the labs into a single organization with separate business units for the company's major markets. To solidify the change, she imposed a standardized price list for testing work. Customer service representatives, instead of engineers, now handle price quotes. The company says that's reduced the wait times to a couple of days from two weeks. The goal is to generate quotes in 24 hours.
That means more globetrotting, while ensuring that her visits to the Bagel will be an oasis of personal time in what has become a 24-hour-a-day career. "There are no such things as holidays, because if there's a U.S. holiday, it's not a holiday in China," she says. "The Bagel serves breakfast all the time."
Bob Tita >> NEXT >>
